text: This is actually somewhat historically accurate.  The man that the vampire Dracula was based off of was Vlad the Impaler--a ruler in what is now Romania.  His name is mostly known for his ruthless and brutal oppression of his people, obviously impalement as well as other unspeakable acts of cruelty.  That being said, he was in fact instrumental in keeping in check the power of the Turks in Europe.  I'd imagine the "sultan" that they mentioned in the trailer is referring to the ruler of the Ottoman empire--whom i'm assuming will be the main antagonist in the story.  At least this might shed (some sort) of light on Vlad's achievements in the wider scope of European history...

text: Meh, when you think about it- AT LEAST it's not like Twilight with the sparkling and the "sexy vampire" stuff. Who knows, they might explain the historical accuracies as for the people who made this ARE professionals.  I liked how they captured the demonic side of Vampires, instead of trying to make them sexy, vampires in general are meant to be fowl, demonic creatures. Sure, maybe some sensuality was shown, but overall I thought they were accurate with the following things:  1. Dracula was a real guy, no arguing about that obviously  2. Dracula's superior power to other vampires, making him different from any other vampire  3. The dark, gritty, hellish side of vampires in general, instead of that sexy bullshit. -pardon my language-  4. I love how they portrayed his backstory, I mean a good man who would do anything to protect his family but eventually become an evil legend. Better than modern day vampiric sexuality  5. Sure, I get we got some critics out there who think this is some ridiculous trash covered with special effects, but who knows- it might do well.  6. I'm not judging your opinions, feel free to criticize, but we should at least give this film a chance, I for one already love it.  -it's also got that dark, Romanian, castlevania feel to it

text: I'm not going to set my expectations extraordinarily high as of yet, but it looks like an interesting take on the Dracula legend having him be an anti hero who embraces Vamparism to save his country. I think it's kind of ignoring how  the historical Vlad was always a man of violent nature throughout his lifetime, but if its done right it could be an interesting way to retell Dracula's story. Especially if this movie can segue into the Bram Stoker story. It would be interesting seeing a bunch for movies showing his transformation from a man trying to save his kingdom, to a cold and calculating immortal being who kills and strikes fear into the hearts of men for his own ambitions.  All I'm saying right now is this film better be rated R or at least have an extensively different  R rated directors cut that keeps the films artistic sensibilities intact. Because if this movie ends up being PG-13, my expectations will drop very low.

text: Based on what I've read of other people's comments, I've come to a few conclusions:  1. Most of the people here have never read Bram Stoker's Dracula... even a lot of the ones who say they have. Dracula has no "real" origin story, so stop saying he does and that this movie is going to contradict it.  2. A lot of people think this movie is going to glorify "evil" as being "good," without considering that this film may be showing a hero's fall from good to evil, or maybe showing that the binary of good and evil doesn't exist, and everything is shades of gray. You know, like real life.  3. Everyone thinks Dracula is the "first" vampire, which means there couldn't possibly be any other vampires that came before him. Again, read the book, guys. Also, if any literary vampire should be considered the "first" modern vampire, it should be Lord Ruthven from John Polidori's "The Vampyre," as he is most likely the progenitor of the modern vampire myth.  4. A lot of people are mad that the film isn't historically accurate to Vlad Tepes. A lot of the people leaving comments about Vlad Tepes are actually citing false information. Also, they seem to forget that this is a fictional film, not a documentary. Vlad Tepes wasn't actually a vampire, guys.  5. Most of the people who want to see this are Castlevania fans. And I'm right there with you guys. This movie has Castlevania written all over it, and I love it.  ...that's all I wanted to say.

text: This is based on the fictional vampire Dracula, not the historical figure, damn people, cool your jets. Yes, Stoker based his character on the historical figure but the title says Dracula, Untold... there is no tagline based on a true story there at all. It's fantasy so cut them some freaking slack. Being a big horror buff this actually looks much more interesting and well thought out/produced than most renditions of Dracula. If you have a complaint about the sort of vampirism do your research on the mythos.  Many Hollywood and literary sources present vampires as both horrific monsters and romantic tragic figures. This films seems to blend the two quite well if the trailer is any indication. Dracula could turn into bats and rats and bugs and wolves and all kinds of things horrible and fantastic. Sometimes he was striking, beautiful and other times horrific and deformed. If anything this movie is tipping its hat to those aspects of the Dracula mythology.  I didn't hear any crappy cancer voice coming out of his mouth. So Batman has bats... whoopty frigging doo. Guess batman rips off Dracula since the novel came way before the comic. There are no original ideas just really good writers who steal ideas and make you think its something new. There's only so many ways you can spin a dark tragic anti hero and this somewhat gothic style of filming does not originate from the Dark Knight movie. Hollywood uses what works and you know what when someone tries something new  the trolling masses crucify it. I'll give you that sparkling vampires are a pretty stupid idea especially attractive to teenage girls but at least someone had the bravery to try something new. You people aren't satisfied with originality and the saying goes something like mimicry is the greatest form of flattery (yes I know i butchered the phrase but you get the gist) but people complain about that too.  If it peaks your interest see it, if you wanna complain go start a forum. Oh and also the judgmental attitudes of a lot of viewers is quite deplorable. Do you even read or watch history related stuff? Vlad might have been a monster by our standards but if you look at his history and what he was facing you might have a bit more sympathy for the man. He saved his countrymen from slavery and death for a time.  To this day he is still hailed as a hero in that part of the world. I believe he may have gone beyond what was necessary but maybe not. He was ludicrously outnumbered with limited resources and very little support from those who commanded him. The tactics while horrible by our standards got the job done, scared away the Turks and saved his people. I'm sure it was less madness and depravity and instead calculated intelligent maneuvering born more out of desperation and the ends justifies the means mentality. If being victorious means you're right then I suppose Vlad chose the right methods wouldn't you agree?

text: Vlad Țepes: One of the few great rulers of Romania that brought fear into his enemies through some unique strategies of battle.  His most definite mark was that he impaled a huge amount of people with no remorse! Despite what most say, HE DID NOT DO THIS FOR PLEASURE! he was impaling only THIEVES, LIERS and invaders of Wallachia, mostly punishing those that opposed the ways of God. There was no jail time or captures. He executed them on sight, impaling them to set an example.  Because he was so straight with his executions and filled his entire country with impaled bodies terrifying everyone, people started to think that he is evil. Until to the point the story of Dracula started to emerge.  Another reason why he was considered evil was that he impaled even a lot of rich people that tried to betray him. Because of this, those that opposed him tried to make the people hate and fear him by spreading FALSE stories in the hope that his support would diminish and he could be taken down from his throne.  Here are the 2 most infamous strategies that he used to defeat the ottoman empire even if he was greatly outnumbered.  1. He and his men chopped off an entire forest and dressed it as soldiers... When the ottoman soldiers arrived, they retreated frightened of the numbers Vlad armies were posing.  2. 'The night attack'. He and a few men dressed as ottomans went into their enemy camp, starting a riot under the reason "Get up and fight, Romanians have dressed as ottomans and are sabotaging our camp!". This way the ottoman forces slaughtered themselves.  After battles, all of the fallen bodies were impaled to set an example.  Make no mistake, the Ottoman forces could have crushed Romanian forces like bugs. The armies used for their campaign were not to conquer, but to recover the tribute Romanians were supposed to give. This means the numbers of soldiers sent to oppose Vlad was fairly low compared with the entire Ottoman armada!  This is a short and very simplified version of the real Dracula history. The legend is nice, but too far from truth. I like that in this movie Vlad is presented as a DEFENDER, ready to sacrifice all that he has for the sake of his family and people. One way or another this is what he actually did, and i hope this movie will resurrect at least the intentions of Vlad.﻿  AND ... DRACU means DEVIL, NOT DRAGON !!!!!!!! Dracul -> The Devil. As one of the many devils of hell. Roughly translating 'Dracula'...'The Deviler' or 'The Devile'

text: I was hoping this would be a refreshing change from the petulant, sex kitten/ teenage vampire trope, but it looks like a petulant, sex kitten/adult vampire trope instead.  Who can honestly say though since the movie has not been released yet. Personally I prefer my vampires to be evil bastards that get their comeuppance with a good whack to the heart, or a healthy blast of ultraviolet radiation.  I realize that religion is part of the vampire mythos, but I’m perplexed by the suggestion that there is something inherently antichristian in making a villain sympathetic, or that these plot devices prove the existence of a messiah, or an antimessiah. text: I find it hilarious that people are arguing about the inaccuracies in this movie. It's fiction, not a documentary. It's not even based on the actual Vlad Tepes, but the fictional vampire Dracula (who was based on Vlad Tepes) So in a nutshell, it's making changes to a fictional character who was already only loosely based on a real person who died hundreds of years ago when recorded history was sketchy at best. Are these the same people who complained about 300? Maybe the problem is making Dracula the hero, or anti-hero in this case since people are arguing in the comments whether or not the original Vlad the impaler could be called anything other than a monster. But that's really irrelevant since almost everyone, especially leaders, would be monsters by our modern definitions of morality and equality. How many movies show the founding fathers interacting with their slaves. How many movies show Columbus to be a monster who pillaged the natives land. How many movies show any male from the past absuing women (I suppose shows like Game of Thrones and Spartacus are the best examples) At the end of the day it's a movie. Enjoy it for what it is. Or don't if it ends up being a bad movie. Then make fun of it all you like.

text: ,,Who was Vlad Dracula?  An Intriguing Figure in The Fifteenth Century  by Benjamin Hugo Leblanc - EPHE-Sorbonne (Paris) &  Laval University (Quebec) Count Dracula is more than 100 years old and still alive! Of course, almost everybody has heard about this Nosferatu: through movies featuring Max Schreck, Bela Lugosi, Christopher Lee or Gary Oldman; in several books, including the recent Vampire Chronicles of Anne Rice, or even in bedtime stories told to us in our childhood. We all have an idea of who or what the Count is. However, on the other hand, Vlad Tepes (Dracula), the historical figure who inspired Bram Stoker’s novel, is definitely less well-known.  Vlad Tepes was born in December 1431 in the fortress of Sighisoara, Romania. Vlad's father, governor of Transylvania, had been inducted into the Order of the Dragon about one year before. The order — which could be compared to the Knights of the Hospital of St. John or even to the Teutonic Order of Knights — was a semi-military and religious society, originally created in 1387 by the Holy Roman Emperor and his second wife, Barbara Cilli. The main goal of such a secret fraternal order of knights was to protect the interests of Christianity and to crusade against the Turks. The boyars of Romania associated the dragon with the Devil and decided to call Vlad's father "Dracul," which in the Romanian language means "Devil;" "Dracula" is a diminutive, meaning "the son of the Devil."   In the winter of 1436-1437, Dracul became prince of Walachia (one of the three Romanian provinces) and took up residence at the palace of Targoviste, the princely capital. Vlad followed his father and lived six years at the princely court. In 1442, in order to keep the Turks at bay, Dracul sent his son, Vlad, and his younger brother, Radu, to Constantinople (today Istanbul) as hostages of the Sultan Murad II. Vlad was held there until 1448. This Turkish captivity surely played an important role in Dracula's upbringing; it must be at this period that he adopted a very pessimistic view of life and learned the Turkish method of impalement on stakes. The Turks set Vlad free after informing him of his father's assassination in 1447. He also learned about his older brother's death and how he had been tortured and buried alive by the boyars of Targoviste.  When he was 17 years old, Vlad Tepes (Dracula), supported by a force of Turkish cavalry and a contingent of troops lent to him by Pasha Mustafa Hassan, made his first major move toward seizing the Walachian throne. Vlad became the ruler of Walachia in July of 1456. During his six-year reign, he committed many cruelties, hence establishing his controversial reputation.  His first major act of revenge was aimed at the boyars of Targoviste for not being loyal to his father. On Easter Sunday of what we believe to be 1459, he arrested all the boyar families who had participated at the princely feast. He impaled the older ones on stakes while forcing the others to march from the capital to the town of Poenari. This fifty-mile trek was quite grueling and no one was permitted to rest until they reached their destination. Dracula then ordered the boyars to build him a fortress on the ruins of an older outpost overlooking the Arges River. Many died in the process. Dracula, therefore, succeeded in creating a new nobility and obtaining a fortress for future emergencies. What is left of the building today is identified as Poenari Fortress (Cetatea Poenari).  Vlad Tepes adopted the method of impaling criminals and enemies and raising them aloft in the town square for all to see. Almost any crime, from lying and stealing to killing, could be punished by impalement. Being so confident in the effectiveness of his law, Dracula placed a golden cup on display in the central square of Targoviste. The cup could be used by thirsty travelers, but had to remain on the square. According to the available historical sources, it was never stolen and remained entirely unmolested throughout Vlad's reign. Crime and corruption ceased; commerce and culture thrived, and many Romanians to this day view Vlad Tepes as a hero for his fierce insistence on honesty and order. It’s worth mentioning that most written sources regarding his reign are based on the numerous propagandistic pamphlets spread by the Germans with the help of their new invention, the printing press.  In the beginning of 1462, Vlad launched a campaign against the Turks along the Danube River. It was quite risky, the military force of Sultan Mehmed II being by far more powerful than the Walachian army. However, during the winter of 1462, Vlad was very successful and managed to gain several victories. To punish Dracula, the Sultan decided to launch a full-scale invasion of Walachia. His other goal was to transform this land into a Turkish province. He entered Walachia with an army three times larger than Dracula's. Finding himself without allies and forced to retreat towards Targoviste, Vlad burned his own villages and poisoned the wells along the way, so that the Turkish army would find nothing to eat or drink. Moreover, when the Sultan, exhausted, finally reached the capital city, he was confronted by a most gruesome sight: hundreds of stakes held the remaining carcasses of Turkish captives, a horror scene which was ultimately nicknamed the "Forest of the Impaled." This terror tactic, deliberately stage-managed by Dracula, was definitely successful. The scene had a strong effect on Mehmed's most stout-hearted officers, and the Sultan, tired and hungry, decided to withdraw (it is worth mentioning that even Victor Hugo, in his Legende des Siecles, recalls this particular incident). Nevertheless, following his retreat from Walachian territory, Mehmed encouraged and supported Vlad's younger brother, Radu, to take the Walachian throne. At the head of a Turkish army and joined by Vlad's detractors, Radu pursued his brother to Poenari Castle on the Arges River. According to legend, this is when Dracula's wife, in order to escape capture, committed suicide by hurling herself from the upper battlements, her body falling down the precipice into the river below, a scene exploited by Francis Ford Coppola's production. Vlad, who was definitely not the kind of man to kill himself, managed to escape the siege of his fortress by using a secret passage into the mountain. He was, however, assassinated toward the end of December 1476.  The only real link between the historical Dracula (1431-1476) and the modern literary myth of the vampire is the 1897 novel. Bram Stoker built his fictional character solely based on the research that he conducted in libraries in London. Political detractors and Saxon merchants, unhappy with the new trade regulations imposed by Vlad, did everything they could to blacken his reputation. They produced and disseminated throughout Western Europe exaggerated stories and illustrations about Vlad's cruelty. Vlad Tepes' reign was, however, presented in a different way in chronicles written in other parts of Europe. (Excerpts from a feature published in Issue #5 of Journal of the Dark, by Benjamin Leblanc).,,

text: Umm, no! Not another Dracula film :-(  I hoped this one would be a historic movie based on the life of Vlad Dracul/Țepeș (Dracul with the sense of Dragonul=The Dragon, from the family emblem). BUT it is not a historic film, though it seems to portray part of the wars with the Ottomans that he waged in his lifetime. Really?! Blood, bats and sharp teeeth? Vlad Dracul is one of the greatest voievods/domnitori that the Romanian states had so far - he gained his notoriety when he refused to pay tribute to The Gate (the ottomans), he punished the nobility who acted against the people or chose the ottoman side. In the end he was the victim of the nobility. He was not a vampire, magician, bat!  Hollywood, fuck off! Leave Vlad Dracul in peace. Thanks!

text: Historical record reveals that the real Dracula's head was chopped off and sent to Turkish Sultan who impaled it on a spear and hung it outside his palace.  Dracula died on the battlefield fighting against an invasion of Turks. His reputation finally caught up with him in a bad way: his army was outnumbered by Turks, so most of his soldiers just switched sides after seeing that the impalement ratio in the other army was significantly lower. His head was chopped off—possibly by his own troops, which would not be surprising—and the head was sent to the Turkish Sultan,

text: This film is loosely based on the 13th Century Hungarian prince named Vlad III Tepes, also known as Vlad The Impaler. It also includes aspects of the fictional character Dracula, which was based on Vlad. The story of Dracula was based on the excessive cruelty Vlad displayed to his enemies and, as the name suggests, was known for impaling them. His father was Vlad II Dracul, from which the name Dracula was conceived, and which was also the name which Vlad III carried forth with slight variation.  His father was also a member of the the group known as Order of the Dragon, which was formed to protect Christianity in the area. This is also displayed in the trailer from the armour worn by the lead which incorporates a dragon design.  In terms of the conflict shown in the trailer, during the mid 13th century Vlad III had conflict with the Ottoman dynasty. This stemmed from an order given by the Ottoman leader, known as Mehmet, to offer a large tax contributing of both money and men, similarly shown in this trailer. Vlad III however refused due to believing that paying such a tax would symbolise the surrender of his land and people to the Ottomans as he solely believed in the freedom and interdependency of his  land and people.  However unlike the trailer suggests Vlad III did not climb a mountain and ask the help of a mysterious old man in order to become a vampire. He was however one of the first members of the The League of Shadows.

text: Let's have this more clear, the first vampire was a human man named Ambrogio. He was an Italian-born adventurer who fate brought to Delphi, in Greece. But in a nutshell a series of blessings and curses transformed this young man into history's first vampire. Specifically, it began with the sun god Apollo (Greek mythology), who in a fit of rage cursed Ambrogio so that his skin would burn should it ever touch sunlight again. Ambrogio's bad luck followed when he ended up gambling away his soul to Hades (Greek mythology), the god of the underworld. The next curse came via Apollo's sister Artemis (Greek mythology), the goddess of the moon and hunting, who made it so that Ambrogio's skin would burn if he touched silver. The blessings came soon after when Artemis, taking pity on the poor young man, gave him the gift of immortality. He would carry his curses - his skin burning by sunlight or silver, but he would live forever in his current form. Not only that, but Artemis also gave him the speed and strength to become a hunter whose skills were second only to her own. Blood-sucking (which, by the way, is called "hematophagy" in case you were curious) is also included in this "blessing". Ambrogio hunts swans and uses their blood as ink to write love poems to his lady Selene. While this may be considered a little creepy by our standards, it wasn't all that unusual in ancient Greece to make do with what you hunted.  Ambrogio later moved back to Italy, now as a full-fledged vampire. Legend traces him to the city of Florence (Firenze), where he creates the first Vampire Clan. We don't know a whole lot about this clan, other than they were most likely willing volunteers - humans who wanted power and immortality, and were willing to trade their souls for it. It was believed that the curse would continue for any vampire where their souls would remain in the Underworld (aka Hades aka Hell), where they could return to claim them, but then could never leave. From what we know of the history of vampires, the clan grew in size and strength, until infighting created something of a "civil war" within the clan, and many vampires left to form their own clans. What happened to Ambrogio and those who stayed with him is largely unknown, though many believe that he still resides somewhere in Florence.

text: The real Dracula is a Romanian hero, named Vlad Tepes, whom was a war hero when fighting off the Turks. Although he was an excessively cruel man, also known as Vlad the impaler, he was also fighting for the protection of his people. The man in Romania is considered a hero for protecting them. However, the legend did grow that he was a vampire, which was a common belief in that region during his era, partially due to his notoriety on how cruel he was. Vlad Dracula Tepes became immortalized by the horror book Bram Stoker's Dracula, which was based off of him, but was a fictional work. That portrayed him as a vampire, obviously. What it looks like Universal Pictures is doing is combining the two Dracula's, the reality and the fiction to create a story on the emergence of Vlad Tepes becoming a vampire. If done right, I personally think it could be genius.

text: In 1436, Vlad II Dracul ascended the throne of Wallachia. He was ousted in 1442 by rival factions in league with Hungary, but secured Ottoman support for his return by agreeing to pay the Tribute to the Sultan.  Vlad II also sent his two legitimate sons, Vlad and Radu cel Frumos, to the Ottoman court, to serve as hostages of his loyalty. After the death of Vlad II Dracul, Radu cel Frumos converted to Islam and entered the service of the Ottoman court.[6]  During his years as hostage, Vlad was educated in logic, the Quran and the Turkish language and works of literature. He would speak this language fluently in his later years.[1] He and his brother were also trained in warfare and riding horses. The boys' father, Vlad Dracul, was awarded the support of the Ottomans and returned to Wallachia and took back his throne from Basarab II and some disloyal Boyars.

text: What a bunch of bullshit. Packaging it as if it's the "untold" true story of Dracula but then showing him turning into bats which is complete Hollywood fictionalized bullshit. I'd love to see JUST ONE writer actually research the real Vlad Dracula; do the damn fact checking and get it right, instead of making up more bullshit and packaging it as non-fiction. I've read every damn book that's ever been written on the real Vlad Dracula and he didn't fucking turn into a swarm of bats. If this movie IS based on the true facts then I think it's a brilliant idea. But based on the word "Untold" in the title and the trailer showing him turning into a swarm of bats it looks more like a bait & switch - trying to sucker people into theaters by making them believe it's non-fiction and only revealing the truth after they've made their money. How the hell is it "Untold" if it's based on the novel Dracula by Irish novelist Bram Stoker? (a story that has already been told LITERALLY 217 times as of 2009).  It's no different than the way they released the book "The Celestine Prophecy", originally marketed as non-fiction and then LATER they admitted that it was complete fiction. The "Celestine Prophecy" was a great book; it's still one of my favorites - but still deceptive in the way it was marketed. Same with "Paranormal Activity" and the "Blair Witch Project". Make people believe it's non-fiction so they'll go see it and then reveal the truth AFTER they've made millions of dollars by deceiving people.

text: Mixed feelings about this.  If there isn't going to be blood or impalings, probably won't care for it too much.  We've seen enough of the well-used mold for heroes and stories in film wearing the masks of classic, well-loved characters.  What there needs to be is a traditional, ambitious, and downright gory remake of Bram Stoker's original novel, perhaps even a remake of Nosferatu; right down to the part where the villainous vampire, ugly and twisted like all vampires should be, drains dry the poor girl and wife of the main character before he himself is turned to dust by the coming sun in his gluttony and thirst for her virgin blood.  THAT is a vampire movie I will pay good money to go see.

When he didn't accept giving tributes and tax, of course thats when the war started in which Vlad announced by killed thousands of Turks whom where also civilians, as a thanks for peace :P Yeah, my point is just... text: For the record, I'm looking forward to this movie.  The problems with many movies these days seems to be more that they are (sadly rightfully so) geared to a less intelligent audience. Many people don't care about the ideals associated with sacrificing oneself for an eternity of hell in a living body. Half of them don't care about ideals at all. Probably why a good amount of the critics said Cloud Atlas was too advanced for most of the viewers. It's probably also why you'll find Star Wars to be a hot topic while Dune and Star Trek are almost ignored. This is mainly due to education itself being undermined and consequently not funded.  Most viewers I've talked to want less reason for a story, more action in the story, and great graphical and sound effects. (don't deny it, almost ALL of the top twenty comments as of posting this talk about shitty effects, even the ones that dislike twilight admit that it's because someone DARED to present vampires as capable of being attractive and good[though yes, pouring sparkles on them was a bit much])  This is why you'll often find viewers who love mainly comedy, horror, action, or psychological thrillers (a fancy name for horror of which its type has been defined multiple ways). They don't truly want to be engaged in the movie. They don't want something to think about and relate to reality. They just want straight entertainment ***(or as I call it when I'm in a rage 'stupid pointless bullshit that encourages people to become even dumber than they were when they began watching it').***  For the people who recognize that and use it to relax, you're fine. For the others? You're fine too. I'm not actually trying to insult you guys though it may sound like it. But different movies appeal to different people. I don't care if the movie/show doesn't have the best effects or the most action. I don't care if the battles are mainly won through talking. I want something to be able to think about and enjoy doing so. I want to walk away from a movie and learn something new... even if solely from a fantasy ideal  ***emphasis on "when I'm in a rage"***

text: I find the direction of this movie quite interesting... a blending of all the Dracula legends and stories into one. For the record, Vlad was no more violent then any other General at the time. Yes he did unspeakable things to his enemies, but no worse then any other conqueror. If anything he was a PR master. He created an image of horror so great that other much larger forces surrounding him (like the Turks) feared attacking. It was during his reign his people experienced one of the longest periods of peace in history.

text: I loved this movie >_> I get everyone has their opinion and all that, but- i mean. Come on. It seems like every movie that's released these days gets the shit nit picked out of it. Honestly, did someone spend money to go see this movie in theaters and just sit there, amidst the amazing surround sound, the entertaining story and progression of events-- and just think "Wow, what a piece of shit. This shouldn't exist." ? Movies are never going to be exactly what you'd hoped or expected, but you can still enjoy what they 'do' bring to your table. That being said, I loved this movie. I happened to think it was a breath of fresh air compared to the vampire fluff we've seen lately- not talking down on Twilight or True Blood- just saying I enjoyed seeing vampires related more so to what the older stories offered-- monsters, deals that come at a cost, powerful figures that are feared and misunderstood, and a greater darkness that haunts the entire story. From another perspective, I suppose I can see how some people might not enjoy it- after all this movie brought to life everything 'I' imagine vampires to be when I think of "vampire." That's what 'I' liked about it. I love Bram Stoker's Dracula, I love Van Helsing, I love Interview with a Vampire, i love the history and mythology adapted into every story-- all of it. Anyways, love it or not- I recommend seeing it.

text: Yet another brainwashing fake movie. True "dracula" had a name, Mircai Batrin. He was a general under Sultan Fatih Mehmet, the ruler of the Ottoman Empire at the time. - After Fatih conquers Constantinople (currently known as Istanbul) he also conquers Bulgaria, Romania and the countries around. Mircai was a child, and ottomans dos not kill children and massacre the people, instead they protect them and share their knowledge and treat them as their own. So when Mircai  grew older he became a soldier in the army, then a general. Fatih gave him the job to "manage" Romania. For a long time no taxes were coming from Mircais area, so Fatih sent some soldiers to check the thing, but Soon after they came he impaled all the soldiers and drank their blood, except 2. He told them to report this to Fatih, and they did. Fatih personally selected a group of huge army and sent them to kill Mircai. And yes, he had a castle, scary as shit we see in movies. After Mircais wife saw the army's size she jumped out of the window to the cliff and killed herself. Then Mircai was cornered by the soldiers at the same spot, he said "Some day I will return, and I will drink all your blood" and jumped out of the window. Soldiers declared victory and went back to report Fatih.

text: This movie kicked A#$! I know the true story of Vlad Tepes or Vlad the Impaler. This movie does a good job a of mixing some of the truths of Vlad the Impaler while still keeping Dracula's legend true to an extent too. Great job by the writers and the actors were perfect for their roles. I love history, enjoy Gothic literature, have written a few stories and have done a bit of acting but nothing major. This movie is worth the money to see at the movie theater. Don't hesitate, if 1) you love real vampires (Not twinkle toes) 2) You enjoy history and know a bit of Vlad Tepes 3) Enjoy tragic hero stories such as Shakespeare and Greek mythology. 4) have read or know a little about Dracula from Bram Stoker's novel. 5) enjoy movies with good plot and fantastic action/ fighting scenes, and great characters. Altogether 10 out 10. Watch this movie if those things apply to you. If not and you want to be a history or literature stickler, then complain and whine about there not being enough documentaries and that movies should be completely accurate or you won't give them a chance and will then whine that the media is driven by hype instead of fact. Otherwise, watch this movie, worth the money and your time.

text: I don't understand whats wrong with people today? I mean obviously this movie has elements and ties to the real man Vlad but it's the origin story of Vlad Dracula the fictional character not the real historical figure man. So whats all this talk about how awful the movie is just because it's not 100 percent historically accurate? If somebody would rather see something about the man himself then try the Discovery Channel or maybe looking it up online. But don't come on here with your bitter cynical remarks and start attacking the people that not only get pissed off by the attitude but really enjoyed the movie. If somebody has an opinion that there should be a movie more centered on Vlad the Impeller thats fine but it's not ok to not only talk poorly about the movie but act as though this opinion of yours is somehow fact. This movie was a great movie and just because somebody thinks there idea is better doesn't make this a bad movie nor does it make what they say fact. Keep such bitter and cynical comments to yourself people. Or at least have the decency to respect others who really enjoyed the film and don't leave such comments please. Or at least respect if others disagree instead of going on such long ass charades of back and forth. Agree to disagree and move on.

text: Why the movie is so bad? Let me explain you! 1- Scenario Mistakes! I watch movie to learn about the beginning of the vampire world and their "chief" Dracula. Also related to Turkish people, who conquered some part of christian world and never push to change their language or religion like other Emparialist states (I think you dont need examples which states I mean!....)?!!! 2- Movie show us that Vlad sold his soul to evil couse of Evil Turks... Turks was coming and killing so he need to.! As movie tells us also, 1st vampire gives a big "historal lesson" to Romanian Prince Vlad!!! He tolds to him like.. text: I loved it :D It was simply everything you would expect after watching this trailer: An action, somewhat funny, somewhat romantic, plain fantasy movie. Great effects, monumental frames, good acting, nice costumes. As to the story it did exactly what was shown here as well; by far not flawless, only very roughly based on something historical (they never claimed it to be a historic movie, so what the hell was everybody expecting? :D), a tiny bit scary, it left lots of loose ends and you didn't always get really into it because the time wasn't there to get acquainted with situations and characters. Maybe this would have been a better story if they did a mini series out of it... anyway, after watching the trailer it was just what I thought it was and I enjoyed every bit of it - exactly what I believe cinema is meant to make you feel! =)  And not to spoiler it, but I specially liked the end - that was surprising indeed ;)

text: Reputation for cruelty Pilate Judging Jesus Christ, National Gallery, Ljubljana, 1463. The Martyrdom of Saint Andrew (1470–1480, Belvedere Galleries) Paintings such as these are said to depict Biblical tyrants with the features of Vlad. Above, as Pontius Pilate, below as a Roman proconsul After Vlad's death, his deeds were reported in popular pamphlets in Germany, reprinted from the 1480s until the 1560s, and to a lesser extent in Tsarist Russia. A typical German pamphlet from 1521 gives numerous examples of lurid incidents, such as the following:[16] He roasted children, whom he fed to their mothers. And (he) cut off the breasts of women, and forced their husbands to eat them. After that, he had them all impaled.[16] Vlad Ţepeş's reputation was considerably darker in Western Europe than in Eastern Europe and Romania. In the West, Vlad III Ţepeş has been characterized as a tyrant who took sadistic pleasure in torturing and killing his enemies.[citation needed] Estimates of the number of his victims range from 40,000 to 100,000.[17] He also had whole villages and fortresses destroyed and burned to the ground.[18] Impalement was Vlad's preferred method of torture and execution. Several woodcuts from German pamphlets of the late 15th and early 16th centuries show Vlad feasting in a forest of stakes and their grisly burdens outside Brașov, while a nearby executioner cuts apart other victims.[19] It has also been said that in 1462 Mehmed II, the conqueror of Constantinople, returned to Constantinople after being sickened by the sight of 20,000 impaled corpses outside Vlad's capital of Târgoviște.[20]

text: „Dracula", romanul gotic scris şi publicat în 1897 de scriitor, a fost inspirat de cronicile medievale săseşti despre Vlad Ţepeş şi metodele sale de tortură practicate în Ţara Românească. Voievodul era prezentat drept un personaj sângeros, de o cruzime ieşită din comun, scrie „România liberă“. Până la lansarea acestui roman, Stoker mai avea patru cărţi, dar niciuna de un prea mare succes. „Dracula“ a fascinat însă publicul, mai ales prin filme şi reinterpretări.  În documentarea romanului, Bram Stoker s-ar fi folosit şi de volumul „History of Moldavia and Wallachia“, scris de istoricul austriac de origine germană Johann Christian Engel, în 1804, unde Ţepeş este descris drept un tiran sângeros. Mai mult, autorul ar fi avut acces şi la Biblioteca Regală din Londra, unde sunt o parte din gravurile săseşti din secolul al XV-lea şi cronicile medievale din colecţiile de la British Museum. În acestea Vlad Ţepeş este un domnitor monstruos, ba chiar vampir care bea sânge de om şi găseşte o mare satisfacţie în cruzimile faţa de oameni.

text: 1456 yılında Fâtih, Wlad'i Eflâk prensligine tayin etmişti. Wlad, kardesi Radul ile birlikte Osmanlı sarayında rehine olarak bulunmuştu. Hüküm sürdüğü memlekete Fâtih'in yardımı ile sahip olmasına ve Pâdişaha karşı dost kalacağına dair yemin etmiş bulunmasına rağmen Wlad, sözünde durmayarak Osmanlılar aleyhine Macarlarla anlasma yapacaktır.Fâtih'in, Karadeniz ve Trabzon'da bulundugu sıralarda, Eflâk'ta bazı hadiseler olmaktaydı. Burada Türklerin "Kazıklı Voyvoda", Macarlarin "Drakula" (Şeytan), Ulahların "Çepelpuç" (Cellad) dedikleri Wlad adında zulüm delisi bir adam, halka idarenin en korkuncunu tattırmaktadır. Bu çılgın adam, vahşi ve insanlık dışı birtakım zevklere sahipti. O, kazıklara vurulmuş ve işkence içinde can vermekte olan Türklerin meydana getirdigi büyük halkanın ortasında, saray halkı ile birlikte yemek yemekten zevk alırdı. Eline Türk esirleri geçince ayaklarındaki derinin yüzülmesini ve meydana çıkan kırmızı etlere tuz ekilmesini, sonra da bunları keçilere yalatmasını emrederdi. Böylece, diri diri ayaklarının derisi yüzülen esirlerin işkencesi, daha büyük olurdu. O, kendisine gönderilen Osmanlı elçilerinin sarıklarını başlarına çiviletmiştir. Fâtih Sultan Mehmed, onu İstanbul'a davet eder. Ancak Wlad, düşmanlarının çokluğundan ve memlekette bulunmadığı bir sırada tac ve tahtının Macarlara verileceğinden korktuğundan, Eflâk'ı düşmanlarına karşı muhafaza edecek bir kuvvetin gönderilmesini rica eder. Bunun üzerine Pâdişah, Silistre Beyi Yunus Bey ile Çakırcıbaşı Hamza Bey'i Eflâk'i beklemek üzere görevlendirir. Yunus Bey ile ÇakırcIbaşı Hamza Bey, Tuna kenarına geldikleri vakit, nehrin donmuş olduğunu görürler. Bununla beraber Tuna'yı geçmek hazırlıkları yaptıkları ve dostluktan başka bir şey ümid etmedikleri, hatta itibar göreceklerini sandıkları bir sırada Wlad'ın büyük bir saldırısına uğrarlar. Bu baskında Yunus Bey şehid, Hamza Bey de esir edilmişti. Wlad, daha sonra Hamza Bey'i öldürerek başını Macar kralına gönderir. Kan dökücü Wlad, aldığı esirlerin tamamını kazığa vurduktan sonra, Osmanlılara ait bazı sehir ve kasabaları tahrip etmekten de çekinmez.Bütün bu olanları haber alan Fâtih Sultan Mehmed, hiddetinden ve üzüntüsünden yerinde duramayarak 150 bin kişilik bir ordu ve 25 büyük, 150 küçük parça deniz kuvveti (nehir donanması) hazırlayarak, Allah'ın kullarına zulm eden bu zâlimi ortadan kaldırmak için Eflâk seferine çıkar (H. 866/1462 M.) Fâtih, Eflâk ortalarına kadar gittiği halde, Wlad'in kuvvetleri ortalarda görünmüyorlardı. Wlad, Fâtih'in, casusları vasıtasiyle önceden haber aldığı bir gece baskını düzenleyerek Pâdişahı öldürmek ister. Fakat bunda muvaffak olamadığı gibi, perişan bir halde canını zor kurtarıp kaçabilir. Osmanlı akıncıları onu bulmak için bütün Eflâk’ı tararlar. Pâdişah da ordusuyla prensliğin başkentine yürür. Şehrin yakınında kazıklanmış 15 bin adamdan kurulu korkunç bir orman görünce nefretle "Devlet kuvvetini böyle kullanmış, tebeasına ve Allah'a karşı bu denlü cinayetler islemiş bir adam, asla itibara layık değildir" der.Yaralı olarak kaçıp Macarlara sığınan Wlad, onlardan yardım ister. Fakat Macar Kralı, hiç yoktan Osmanlılarla bir anlaşmazlığa düşmek istemediğinden bu yardımı yapmamış, hatta Wlad'i yakalayarak haps etmişti. Öte taraftan Osmanlılar, Wlad'in kardeşi Radul'u oniki bin duka yıllık vergiye bağlayarak Eflâk prensliğinin başına getirdiler. Böylece Eflâk, mümtaz bir eyâlet haline getirilerek, Osmanlılara sıkıca bağlanmış oldu. Wlad, Radul'un ölümü üzerine zindandan kaçıp tekrar idareyi ele almak istediyse de öldürülerek kesik başı memleket memleket dolaştırılır.

text: I LOVED this movie. It was awesome and I was completely emersed into the story, in fact I didn't even notice how long I sat in the movie theater watching credits after. I don't understand people complaining about inaccuracies in history. It's a movie of fiction, not a documentary. It doesn't have to be 100% right all the time, I say this as a major fan of studying history. When I go to the movies I don't expect it to be accurate unless it says so. And everyone is entitled to an opinion, you don't have to like it but if someone says it's their favorite vampire movie that doesn't mean you get to say your opinion is better and state it as a fact. You can also state your opinion in a better, more intelligent way then simply saying, "it was crap." I mean if someone did that to your favorite movie you'd probably be like, "how is it crap? text: I will give that movie a 5/10 because of all this badass concept turning to a fatigued film through wrong camera angles and screenplay. It could easily be an 8/10  Seriously having him fight one thousand soldiers with bare hands and showing all this with a pathetic camera movement through a sword's reflection didn't pay him any respect at all. I was expecting something like Matrix where Neo VS Smiths was well demonstrated and we saw Neo counter them all despite getting hit. The same should have been done here with Dracula getting hit and fighting back. Instead of this he just punched and pushed some of them, then took a halberd and the rest battle was a sword reflection with 1v1 battles.   What I wanna point out is that Hollywood nowadays will not give as powerful cinematography in action sequences. Most movies have shaky events happening in the blink of an eye or one-two hits in just one shot and then moving fast to another shot of the same shaky speed.   We need bigger action sequences in shots. Demonstrate his superior speed and swordsmanship. That is all. Despite all this I enjoyed the movie and the final battle in the room of silver coins was badass as hell.

text: FATİH VE KAZIKLI VOYVODA (DRAKULA)   1456 yılında Fâtih, Wlad'i Eflâk prensligine tayin etmişti. Wlad, kardesi Radul ile birlikte Osmanlı sarayında rehine olarak bulunmuştu. Hüküm sürdüğü memlekete Fâtih'in yardımı ile sahip olmasına ve Pâdişaha karşı dost kalacağına dair yemin etmiş bulunmasına rağmen Wlad, sözünde durmayarak Osmanlılar aleyhine Macarlarla anlasma yapacaktır.Fâtih'in, Karadeniz ve Trabzon'da bulundugu sıralarda, Eflâk'ta bazı hadiseler olmaktaydı. Burada Türklerin "Kazıklı Voyvoda", Macarlarin "Drakula" (Şeytan), Ulahların "Çepelpuç" (Cellad) dedikleri Wlad adında zulüm delisi bir adam, halka idarenin en korkuncunu tattırmaktadır. Bu çılgın adam, vahşi ve insanlık dışı birtakım zevklere sahipti. O, kazıklara vurulmuş ve işkence içinde can vermekte olan Türklerin meydana getirdigi büyük halkanın ortasında, saray halkı ile birlikte yemek yemekten zevk alırdı. Eline Türk esirleri geçince ayaklarındaki derinin yüzülmesini ve meydana çıkan kırmızı etlere tuz ekilmesini, sonra da bunları keçilere yalatmasını emrederdi. Böylece, diri diri ayaklarının derisi yüzülen esirlerin işkencesi, daha büyük olurdu. O, kendisine gönderilen Osmanlı elçilerinin sarıklarını başlarına çiviletmiştir. Fâtih Sultan Mehmed, onu İstanbul'a davet eder. Ancak Wlad, düşmanlarının çokluğundan ve memlekette bulunmadığı bir sırada tac ve tahtının Macarlara verileceğinden korktuğundan, Eflâk'ı düşmanlarına karşı muhafaza edecek bir kuvvetin gönderilmesini rica eder. Bunun üzerine Pâdişah, Silistre Beyi Yunus Bey ile Çakırcıbaşı Hamza Bey'i Eflâk'i beklemek üzere görevlendirir. Yunus Bey ile ÇakırcIbaşı Hamza Bey, Tuna kenarına geldikleri vakit, nehrin donmuş olduğunu görürler. Bununla beraber Tuna'yı geçmek hazırlıkları yaptıkları ve dostluktan başka bir şey ümid etmedikleri, hatta itibar göreceklerini sandıkları bir sırada Wlad'ın büyük bir saldırısına uğrarlar. Bu baskında Yunus Bey şehid, Hamza Bey de esir edilmişti. Wlad, daha sonra Hamza Bey'i öldürerek başını Macar kralına gönderir. Kan dökücü Wlad, aldığı esirlerin tamamını kazığa vurduktan sonra, Osmanlılara ait bazı sehir ve kasabaları tahrip etmekten de çekinmez.Bütün bu olanları haber alan Fâtih Sultan Mehmed, hiddetinden ve üzüntüsünden yerinde duramayarak 150 bin kişilik bir ordu ve 25 büyük, 150 küçük parça deniz kuvveti (nehir donanması) hazırlayarak, Allah'ın kullarına zulm eden bu zâlimi ortadan kaldırmak için Eflâk seferine çıkar (H. 866/1462 M.) Fâtih, Eflâk ortalarına kadar gittiği halde, Wlad'in kuvvetleri ortalarda görünmüyorlardı. Wlad, Fâtih'in, casusları vasıtasiyle önceden haber aldığı bir gece baskını düzenleyerek Pâdişahı öldürmek ister. Fakat bunda muvaffak olamadığı gibi, perişan bir halde canını zor kurtarıp kaçabilir. Osmanlı akıncıları onu bulmak için bütün Eflâk’ı tararlar. Pâdişah da ordusuyla prensliğin başkentine yürür. Şehrin yakınında kazıklanmış 15 bin adamdan kurulu korkunç bir orman görünce nefretle "Devlet kuvvetini böyle kullanmış, tebeasına ve Allah'a karşı bu denlü cinayetler islemiş bir adam, asla itibara layık değildir" der.Yaralı olarak kaçıp Macarlara sığınan Wlad, onlardan yardım ister. Fakat Macar Kralı, hiç yoktan Osmanlılarla bir anlaşmazlığa düşmek istemediğinden bu yardımı yapmamış, hatta Wlad'i yakalayarak haps etmişti. Öte taraftan Osmanlılar, Wlad'in kardeşi Radul'u oniki bin duka yıllık vergiye bağlayarak Eflâk prensliğinin başına getirdiler. Böylece Eflâk, mümtaz bir eyâlet haline getirilerek, Osmanlılara sıkıca bağlanmış oldu. Wlad, Radul'un ölümü üzerine zindandan kaçıp tekrar idareyi ele almak istediyse de öldürülerek kesik başı memleket memleket dolaştırılır.

text: Yes it's a fantasy movie and it can follow any scenario. Vlad III. is a historical character and maybe a hero to Romanian. However Mehmed II. is another historical character and a hero to another nation. If you want to change to historical events here, then you should not use historical names. If you want to tell the "untold" story then you could have called him just "sultan" and make him fight a random sultan. So therefore you could bypass all the "haters". Other way,  you are killing a historical person in an irrelevant place with an irrelevant way by an irrelevant person which is so dumb. (And nothing close to an "untold" story)  The truth is: The war was started because Vlad III. did not pay the tribute (In the movie cause is Vlad's denial of giving 1000 children to Mehmed.) Vlad the Impaler in fact could not protect his home, lost the war against Mehmed the Conqueror and betrayed by Hungary in 1462. Yet his tactics were unique in his own way, like poisining all the water supplies on the land and releasing sicked prisoners among Ottomans and impaling Ottoman soldiers to demoralize the enemy. However he was killed by Ottomans around 1470s as his head was impaled into a spear by Mehmed. (Spoiler)

text: I saw that lots of people have disliked this movie, so I decided to watch it to know why. AND I FUCKING FELL IN LOVE WITH LUKE EVANS OMG  I truly loved the movie, the atmospher, the way they "built" the plot, and the sets are absolutely beautiful. But I don't get why people are so annoyed about the story.   I mean, not every movie adaptation is supposed to fit perfectly the story from which it took his main elements. One of the most interesting thing about an "adaptation" of a book is the way the directors see the story and the way they artistically change it according to their point of view. Cinema is a form of art quite free and that's why it's interesting. Moreover, when they decide to make a movie, directors don't sign a "faithfulness charter" saying they really have to follow the original storyline. A book is a book. A movie is a movie. They're both different. Please, stop always wanting every ""adaptation"" to be absolutely true to the original format. Try to consider a book as a book and a movie as a movie. Then, you will be able to criticize each format and work.  Obviously, I don't mean to offend anyone, this is just my point of view :)  I wish you all a great day, wherever you are on Earth.

text: Lol at these people saying how Dracula means the devil. Dracula means that in modern Romanian language, but if you actually have read anything about this man, you will see that Dracul meant the Dragon, and it comes from Latin name for dragon, "draco", and Draculea (reading: Dracula) was a diminutive of Dracul. His father Vlad II Dracul, got the epithet Dracul because he was in the Order of the Dragon which is the Order that was fighting against spreading of Islam, and was fighting to protect Christians in Europe from the Ottoman Turks. It was founded by King Sigismund of Hungary, and later the Holy Roman Emperor. In Latin, the Order was called "Ordo dracorum". So Dracula's father was actually Vlad II the Dragon, and not the Devil, like people today think. So Dracula was something like Dragonling or something.  P.S Dracula was a hero, like anyone who has fought the Turks at that time, because Turks were bloody cruel savages, and the Christian population under them had it really hard and bad.

text: Imagine a guy disguised as a Janissary and attacking in the middle of the night a camp of 120.000 Turks with some 3000 men of his own, disguised as well as Turks. He went right in the middle of the camp, seeking to kill the Sultan. Luckily for him, he was not there at that moment, but Vlad the Impaler managed to kill dozens of his high commanders, setting the whole camp in fire, and escape as the rest of the Turks woke up only to find a massive chaos, and everyone cutting each other throats. In the morning, that raid left behind some 50.000 dead, most of them  being from the fights among different troops in the Ottoman Empire. Now you know what Night Attack at Târgovişte was.   He practically invented the Special Ops and commando units. Oh, when Turks managed to track his movements, using the marks left by the horses on the ground, and surrounded him in a castle, they found an empty place filled with impaled ranking ottoman officers. Because  the horseshoes were deliberately mounted in reverse, just to give the impression he is retreating somewhere, when in fact he and all his troops were going  the opposite way.   If anyone is interested, google for Battle of Podul Inalt Vaslui, 1475 (the bloodiest of the middle ages), and his cousin, Stefan cel Mare, from the Order of the Dragon, as well.

text: Honestly as I understand storytelling, there are no limits to reinterpreting myths, fairy tales, legends, and folklore, its been that way since Grimm's Fairy Tales, and even way back during the days of Pagan Gods, to lock down imagination and exploration of such legends into "Uh actually in the original blah blah blah Hollywood ruins stuff blah blah blah" is in my brutally honest opinion, utter horseshit.  Yeah, Disney edits the fairy tales and legends of the source material, that doesn't mean its weak or broken.  Yeah so what if Hollywood movie pagan gods and Marvel pagan gods have more of morality than their original?  Yeah so what if they made Dracula a good guy in some interpretations of stories?  I say to you all, *so fucking what?*  Oh yeah never mind the good these interpretations had done or other stories they've inspired or how happy they make people, nope, better off without 'em. Seriously, imagination and wonder has gone flat. Chained and bound by 'realism', 'genuine consequences', and 'don't tamper with the original' unless it involves making it into a angsty Game of Thrones wannabe.

HE BURNED HIS OWN PEOPLE ALIVE ,just because he didn't like having poor people in his kingdom*  And that was his plan to get rid of poverty! I advice his fans to follow him .. Ps:this is just one of the things he did with his people ;not to mention what he did to Hungarians or Turks, Hungarians hate him..He actually never won a war  "face to face" with turks ,just by betraying them and killing the people they send to deliver a message.  He was the littéral meaning of a *psychopath* ,his love for *Blood* and seeing it was the reason for the *vampire* name. text: I caught part of this movie on cable and vaguely recalled the trailer and that it didn't receive good reviews and, lo and behold, I actually liked what I saw, so yesterday when I was scrolling through On Demand, I said what the hell, clicked on it, and REALLY liked it to the point where I went "I wanna see a goddamn sequel." I mean, frankly, this is the only Dracula movie I've enjoyed since the Christopher Lee Hammer films when I was a kid, and, no, I'm not gonna sit here and say this was anything like them or true to Bram Stoker's vision or a great period film or historically accurate—fuck that. This was a straight up superhero, or rather anti-hero, origin movie with a tragically dark but noble main character who is frigging badass. Dude kills a thousand soldiers in his first battle having superpowers—a THOUSAND—take THAT, Punisher! He fucks up at least a thousand more with his giant fucking BAT FIST—take THAT, Batman! It's like if you're gonna reenvision a character like this, just go "fuck it," all that counts is you tell a good, moving story, have some cool action and nasty bad guys, throw in some romance and emotional shit for the ladies, and voila. Yeah, maybe someday someone will come along and do a totally faithful adaptation of the book, but until then: na-na-na-na-na-na-na-na—DRAC-MAN!

text: J'en ai vu des NAVETS et des BOUSES mais alors là ce fill Dracula Untold en est une ENORME ! Je viens de le regarder sur Netflix il est réellement d'une médiocrité ahurissante. De la propagande et bourré de désinformations. Le grand méchant Musulman envahissant l'Europe et Dracul comme  seul sauveur et rampart pour éviter que les méchants musulmans s'emparent de l'Europe. Mdr et pourtant je suis de confession Catholique j'dis ça j'dis rien. Quand je disais bourré de désinformations c'est aussi parce-que c'est du grand foutage de gueule, est-ce que quelqu'un a réellement cru que les Turcs donc Ottomans parlent l'Arabe et l'écrivent aussi ?  Euh cherchez l'erreur. Les paraboles ne manquent pas on essaye insidieusement de faire l'amalgame car le film est remplit de séquences où on voit l'écriture Arabe ainsi que des drapeaux flottant ornées de signes et de mots en langue Arabe or là où on nous prend réellement pour des cons c'est que juste les Turcs ne sont ni Arabe, ni ne parle Arabe, ni même l'écrivent. Ils ont leur langue, leur littérature et leur écriture qui est plus proche des écritures européennes et à la fois des pays de L'Est. Le réalisateur et scénaristes et producteurs usent de signe et de références Historique, les détournent et s'en servent vicieusement pour placer dans le film des amalgames éhontés. Ou alors ceux qui ont fabriqué cette merde de film sont totalement cons et emplit de clichés ou préjugés. Il aurait fallu qu'il fasse des recherches d'histoire. Faut croire qu'ils pensaient et pensent sûrement encore que nos voisins Turcs parlent et écrivent en Arabe. La seule chose qu'ils ont en rapport avec le Moyen-Orient c'est la religion et encore pas tous sont musulmans certains sont chrétiens tout comme pas tous dans les pays Arabes sont musulmans car beaucoup sont chrétiens. Mais encore une fois j'dis ça j'dis rien. De plus les Ottomans autrement dit les Turcs sont ceux qui ont exporté l'Islam un peu partout dans l'Afrique et Afrique du Nord. Non mais sérieusement j'etais en train d'éclater quand j'ai visionné les scènes avec les drapeaux pseudos Turcs ornées de cette belle langue qu'est L'Arabe  (qui de plus est aussi très usité dans la languz française car faisant partie intégrante d'elle). J'en ai littéralement pleuré de rire tellement c'est hilarant. Mais sérieusement ils sont idiots ceux qui ont fait ce films. De plus moi qui suis fan de l'histoire originelle de Dracula et du livre Roman sur ce comte vampire mais aussi sur la vraie histoire du compte Dracul qui a effectivement combattu les Ottomans mais justement l'histoire la vraie est toute autre et non pas comme elle est véhiculée a travers ce film ou plutôt cette bouse qu'ils ont osé appelé un film. A la rigueur s'ils avaient respecté les faits, les personnages historiques, les personnes mythologiques ok ca passerait mais là cette merde hollywoodienne m'a fait presque vomir au final. Ah qu'on m'explique d'où sort ce gus enfermé dans qa grotte et qui donne le pouvoir de vampire au Comte Dracula ?  Ah oui c'est vrai faut pas être Einstein pour comprendre que ce personnage est juste là pour faire de valoir à une possible suite sur grand ecran. Markting et marketing. Quand au scenario, acteurs et décors ils sont tout autant dans la médiocrité. Ca vole au ras des pâquerette les répliques toutes prêtes à l'emploi on les as vu venir. C'est du pur réchauffé bien puant. Vu et rererevu donc mais cette fois dans la médiocrité totale. Curieusement ils avaient fait ce film en insérant un paquet de désinformations pour déverser de la  bonne vieille propagande bien de chez nous juste quand des sujets et thèmes sont d'actualités. J'ai perdu 1h32 de ma vie. Jaurais mieux fait de sortir me promener et profiter de lon jour et we prolongé avant la reprise du travail lundi. Quel gachi.

text: When the Catholic Hungarians invaded Orthodox Romania, the Romanian king were looking for an alliance with the Ottoman Empire.   To celebrate this alliance, the Romanian king gave 2 princes, so they could educate themselves in one of the world's best education cities, Edirne. The Romanian king were holding on to the oldest son, because he would become the next Romanian king.   Time passed and Mehmet the 2nd became the Ottoman sultan in Edirne.   The Catholic Hungarians invaded Romania again, and this time they captured the Romanian king and his oldest son. The king and the son were tortered, blinded and buried alive.   When Mehmed heard about this, he went to his childhood friend Vlad, and gave him several thousand Janissaries, so that Vlad could avenge his father.   When Vlad came to Romania, he was captured by the Catholic Hungarians. The Hungarian king, who had brutally killed his father and older brother, asked if Vlad would become a subject working for him. Vlad accepted the deal and started to kill innocent muslim villagers, who were most often women and children. Vlad was even getting money from the Pope, in Rome, to continue with his genocide. There are reports Vlad sent to the Pope, which are still open for public in Rome today.   When Mehmed heard about this, he gave some Janissaries to Vlad's brother, Radu the handsome (he was famous among the girls in Istanbul, hence the name). Radu took back the throne of Romania.   When Vlad was killed, his body parts were sent to the capital, and put on the city walls (the only time Ottoman Empire did this).   The reason Vlad is connected to vampirism is because he used to drink red wine from the skulls of innocent children.  Some even say that he drank blood from freshly cut heads.   More interestingly, this guy is considered a national hero in Romania, when in fact he betrayed the Romanian nation and his family by working for the murderer of his family and his people.

text: This movie is bollocks. It might seem cool at first but historically it's so inaccurate and wrong. The movie is painful to watch knowing the history between Ottomans, and Vlad.  Now I hear some people saying "Oh, no kidding, we thought Dracula was a vampire that can turn into bats..." But in the end this whole movie is made to stain reputation of Ottomans. It's full of false accusations against Ottomans, and trying to make Vlad look nice and not evil. In reality Vlad put Muslims into spikes around his castle, drinks human blood (some sources say he loved eating bread with blood)... I'll give you an example; think about William Wallace's movie "Braveheart" know imagine it's a fantastic movie but the hero is Longsharks and he's got fantastic abilities and kills Wallace. And while doing it movie tries to make it seem like Longsharks is actually good... (Though Wallace's got beaten to Longsharks, Mehmed The Conqueror killed Vlad in real life lol).

text: This trailer doesnt give it justice. The trailer makes the film feel and look like shit.  It's very different than this trailer protrays   It's a well written story.  It isn't rock-n-roll rock'em sock'em weak children crap stories.  The subject matter is serious.  The story is well-paced.  Something you can't tell from this terrible trailer.   People should also check out the deleted scenes.  Several of them, especially, the Witch in the Gingerbread House scene are very good.  It's the 2nd best Dracula movie, behind Bram Stoker's Dracula (by Copola).   Another great Dracula like movie is: Let the Right One In.  Check out the original Swedish and the surprisingly good adapted American version.  It is about two children (girl -- vampire), and a boy.
